9.50am News from the middle is that the pitch is still in good condition. Former Australian batsman and now TV commentator Mike Hussey says today will be the best batting conditions of the Test.

Robert Brown: "I predict Australia will be bowled out for under 150, and then Pakistan, will go on and win test, my crystal ball has spoken"

Saad: "It'll be interesting to see how the Marsh brothers handle this innings, both made very low scores in the first test. "

Shaun Marsh will join Aaron Finch at the crease first up after nightwatchman Peter Siddle fell off the last ball of day one. Mohammad Abbas made the two early breakthroughs again for Pakistan and will be a threat this morning.

Good news for Pakistan, Osman Samiuddin is reporting from the ground that Sarfraz will keep wicket and captain today having recovered well enough from his elbow issue. There is some bruising from the blow but no structural issues.

Marnus Labuschagne did an interview before play this morning: "At the end of the day, if you gave us 280 at the start of the day, we definitely would've taken it. That said, we also had an opportunity to get them out for lesser"

"The catch was a funny one. Not sure how I held onto it. I saw it come off the bat, didn't really react to it. It hit my groin, and then as I was turning - or swiveling - I saw the ball in the corner of my eye, and that's when I caged in and try to catch the ball, and it just stuck in like a diamond. I love fielding in general, but especially fielding up close when the ball is spinning, it's exciting."

"It's always good to contribute with the ball. I got that key breakthrough but I also lost a review. I never go too hard on a review, but I didn't think the ball was going over, so I asked for the review. But none of us knew there was bat-first"

9.30am, Day Two Good morning and welcome back to Abu Dhabi for day two of this second Test between Pakistan and Australia. Alex Malcolm in commentary with you this morning and Sreshth Shah will be along later this morning.

It was an incredible day yesterday with 12 wickets falling for on day one of an Abu Dhabi Test for the first time. The day belonged to Nathan Lyon who took four wickets in six balls to help Australia bowl out Pakistan for 282. Daniel Brettig compared Lyon's performance to his last visit to Abu Dhabi.

But there were two stand out performances from Pakistan with the bat. Fakhar Zaman made 94 on debut before falling to Marnus Labuschagne. Sarfraz Ahmed played an outstanding innings and also fell six short of a century. Osman Samiuddin analysed Sarfraz's performance.

There are concerns around Sarfraz's elbow after copping a blow from Mitchell Starc. He took an excellent catch last night but there were concerns post play that he may not keep today. No news yet on whether he will be replaced.

5.15pm It's stumps and what an eventful day we've had. Twelve wickets. Stunning display of spin bowling, a calculative 94 by a debutant, a masterclass in playing spin by a captain, bagful of tricks by a part-timer and then finally two late scalps by a real rockstar. All this means Pakistan have a slight edge at the end of what has been an enthralling day of Test cricket. Pakistan can walk off satisfied after the Test looked headed to the abyss at 57 for 5 one hour into the day after Sarfraz won a good toss.

Ibrarhunzai : "Can we have one more over from Abbas? Please, please, please."

Remember, there's turn and sharp turn, but the bounce has been consistent right through. Batting will be challenging and spinners will increasingly come into the picture as the Test progresses.

If today was anything to go by, we should be in for lots of fun tomorrow. There's plenty of post-day coverage on ESPNcricinfo. Osman Samiuddin will bring you the Pakistan analysis, Daniel Brettig has Australia covered. Danyal Rasool has the match bulletin ready, so do dig in if you may have missed any portion of play. Hope you've enjoyed our coverage today. Until tomorrow, this is Shashank Kishore saying goodbye on behalf of Alex Malcolm.

First time in Abu Dhabi that 12 wickets have fallen on day one. Incredible, isn't it?
